{
  "texts": [
    "Early deep learning models for intent classification used Long Short-Term Memory networks (LTSM) [11] and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) [12].",
    "These models achieved state-of-the-art results on several benchmark datasets, but they were limited by their inability to capture long-range dependencies in text.Transformers-based models, such as BERT and RoBERTa [2], [3], have overcome this limitation by using the transformer architecture [13].",
    "Transformers can learn global dependencies between words in a sentence, which allows them to capture more nuanced semantic information.",
    "This has led to significant improvements in the performance of many NLP benchmarks, and in particular of intent classification.",
    "In [14] the authors present a modification of the pre-trained BERT network that uses siamese and triplet network structures to derive semantically meaningful sentence embeddings."
  ]
}